European inflation slipped into food
Rapid inflation, recorded in the euro area, is due first of all to the rapid growth in the price of food products.
The increase in prices in the month of November has been higher than expected in the 13 countries of the euro area, recording - after 2.6 percent of the month of October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent - announced the Statistical Office of the Union based in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts only gave as likely 3 percent - announced the Bloomberg.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the US, British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut the basic interest, on the pretext that the decline, along with rising commodity prices and the reduction in forced unemployment, would lead to a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least close to two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: "you have to negotiate" on inflation so that it doesn't have to intervene on this issue at a later stage.
Inflation of 3.3 percent, recorded in Germany, broke the twelve-year record; while in Spain it rose from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
Inflation skyrocketed in the euro area as a result of rampant food and energy prices.
Wheat prices at the end of the year increased by 88 per cent and soya prices reached their peak since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil on the world market increased this year by 52 percent, reaching black gold by nearly $100 a barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will rise from the current 2.1 per cent to 2.5 per cent, while by 2009 it will fall to 1.9 per cent.
According to analysts, annual inflation will continue in the next 3 or 4 months around 3 percent, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, during 2008 the ECB is expected to reduce interest rates twice.
Gallup foresees a government crisis
After a long stalemate, by early December the support of the Alliance of Young Democrats increased significantly, reaching its peak level since 2002, while the Gallup never experienced such a low level - 13 percent - in the case of socialists.
The difference in the case of the safe voters of the parties - due to the greater firmness of the voters of the opposition - would mean a support of more than two thirds (71 percent) against the support of one fifth for the socialists (20%).
According to the survey, the Democratic Forum and the Alliance of Free Democrats would not reach the limit necessary to have any parliamentary scandal: their support within the entire population is two percent.
Among the sure voters there are one percent more sympathizers on both sides.
The economic environment continued to deteriorate even compared to the previous lowest point - it has never been so high, 41 percent the proportion of those who judged the country's economic situation especially bad, while another 46 percent believe the situation is quite bad.
Families, after the most hopeful expectations of spring and summer, are now more pessimistic about changing their own economic situation.
With regard to the next year, the majority of the population was experiencing a deterioration in the situation and only one tenth expected improvement.
In December, 71 per cent of those consulted, a figure higher than any previous Gallup survey, estimated that the President of Government performed his duties rather poorly than well.
13 percent of those consulted trust or rely heavily on Ferenc Gyurcsány, while Viktor Orbán has 38 percent of those consulted.
54 percent of the population doesn't trust the Head of Government at all and 27 percent don't trust the president of the Young Democrats Alliance.
One of the indicators of the configuration of the political situation is that, what proportion of society thinks it is possible to control the discontent experienced with the person of the Head of Government without a change of government.
While after the October riots last year 35 percent estimated that it would be desirable to keep the Government and the Head of Government in power, currently this proportion is only 20 percent, while the relative majority (33%) believes that the only solution is the holding of new elections.
Interest in the referendum is characterized by the fact that 60 percent of respondents to the question about participation responded that they would surely participate and another 20 percent said they are likely to participate.
By comparison, in "a general election to be held this Sunday" only 55 percent of the population would surely participate and another 15 percent believe their participation likely. Based on the current intentions of the voters there is no doubt about the outcome of the popular consultation.
Seventy-four percent of the population would disapprove of the payment of study fees, 79 percent of the medical consultation service and 84 percent of hospital care.
If we look at these proportions only among the safe participants in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 per cent of voters would reject the introduction of study rights, payment for medical consultations and hospital care.
The most expensive is the Auchan, the Tesco has quintupled its prices
The average price level increase of 16 percent was maintained by the hypermarkets of Budaörs' gold trading triangle, with the difference that VAT has not been increased this year.
Article by Napi Gazdaság
This year also increased by an average of 16 percent in the commercial golden triangle of Budaörs the usual Christmas basket of the daily Napi, but in all hypermarkets there was a growth well above the thousand HUF.
As prices in food supermarkets had already been "shot" in December last year, this was not the case with a drastic percentage increase compared to the high starting point.
However, it is obviously frightening for consumers that what they were able to buy last year at a price well below the nine thousand HUFs, today they cannot do even for ten thousand.
The Napi basket in the hypermarkets studied exceeded with a minimum of 91 HUF the psychological limit of ten thousand HUF.
And the highest-value basket was 10,573 HUF.
(in 2003 that basket cost 6800 HUF.)
The price of Unicum liqueur and fish remained almost at the previous year's level, but there was a sharp increase in turkey breast fillet, nut and poppy seed.
The price of wheat flour and bread followed the data of the Central Statistical Office, although in the Auchan we have also found a kilo of bread for the price of 139 HUF.
Competition did not reduce the price of the product to less than 200 HUF.
It was equally surprising in this shop that the price of the Coca-Cola with a redeemable bottle of two liters cost less than 200 HUF, so that this product, even with the price of the bottle, cost only 257 HUF.
However, in Napi Auchan's basket it was the most expensive, while Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, compared to last year's Christmas prices, Cora increased with 15, while Tesco and Auchan with about 18 percent the prices listed in Napi's basket.
Comparing the values of last year's most expensive basket with that of this year's cheapest basket, the difference has been 12 percent, while growth between last year's cheapest and the most expensive basket of this year has been 21 percent.
Average growth was 1480 HUF.
Last year the average price growth was 1206 HUF, so during last year's Christmas in prices the increase in VAT was felt.
It was precisely this process that destroyed trade, that supermarkets were visibly unable to decide on the price margin to apply for each product and to calculate the effect of the price change on consumption.
(If the trader misplans the speed of circulation of a product, he may lose an important profit in the margin that fits the volume of sales.)
The increase in the price of Napi's basket reached such extremes as a result of the increase in VAT, the most expensive being 1720 HUF higher than the value recorded in 2006, while at the cheapest the difference was only 844 HUF.
No such extremes occurred this year, as the highest price of now has been 1630 HUF more than last year and the cheapest also increased with 1284 HUF.
Comparing the two Christmas seasons, there was a catastrophic increase in prices in less than 20 months, in hypermarkets the price of consumer goods of first need grew more than 30 percent.
(However this does not necessarily confirm the figures of the Central Bureau of Statistics: this office, in the case of some staple foods, recorded in the 12-month interval a price increase of more than 30 percent.
For example, in addition to wheat, also in the case of egg.)
According to Napi's basket, in the latter case this seems almost impossible, because in the price of this product that was quite expensive already last year compared to the base, it was recorded, in the worst cases only a 10 percent increase in prices.
According to all the indices, flour suppliers have a stronger position than egg suppliers, being able to impose the drastic increase in prices even on multinationals.
Hypermarkets do not complain in the gold trading triangle, they constantly talk about positive results.
According to our experiences, most of the consumers in the three shops visited are no longer interested in prices.
Of all the products they buy large quantities, taking the preserved foods by pallets.
On Wednesday morning, in all three stores large queues were formed ahead of the boxes because the number of customers suddenly increased.
However, we have information that in the interior of the country sales volumes are lower, many multinationals complain to survey institutes because income falls short of their plans and not only in the case of food, but also in the case of household appliances.
Many hospitals save on disinfectants
Several thousand infections have been recorded in hospitals this year, first of all due to the improper application of antibiotics.
The prevailing hygiene circumstances in hospitals, the overcrowding of the beds and the overload of the staff do not favor the control of the infections - says the doctor-head of department of the National Center of Epidemiology.
In many hospitals it is saved even with disinfectants.
Not long ago, MRSA contagion has been diagnosed in the trauma department of János Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of infection occurred in this same hospital at the beginning of the year.
A person injured in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient soon afterwards had to return to the hospital as a result of MRSA contagion and since then no major surgery has been possible due to the presence of the bacteria in his body.
Until December 10 of this year, 1094 cases of hospital infection caused by multi-resistant agents have been registered in the Nosocomialis Surveillance National System - said Karolina Böröcz, medical chief of department of the National Center for Epidemiology.
This means that in hospitals this number of infections caused by multi-resistant agents has surely been recorded, and the rest have no information.
About two thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
One third of humans carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without causing any disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. inflammation of the throat, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once it is applied exaggeratedly or improperly to antibiotics, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics become very resistant to antibiotics and rapidly spread under inadequate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, e.g. wound infections or septicaemia in the first place in patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, patients with weakened bodies, the elderly or people of low weight.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of Hospital János there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are daily in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Antibiotic resistant
"These patients are isolated, the nursing staff treats them in rubber and mask gloves and there are antibiotics suitable for their treatment" - said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalised patients are previously examined for MRSA presence in their body, but even so infection cannot be avoided in all cases.
It is not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent hospital infections of MRSA in most cases, however the current national hospital circumstances do not favour the prevention of formation and contagion with multiresistant pathogens - says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate the sick who carry MRSA in their body.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
This is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not fund these medical examinations.
So most of the cases come to light when MRSA infections are already visible in the patient - said the doctor-head of department of the epidemiological center.
The European Union makes strict mandates for the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological conditions.
Efforts should be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is directed, that is, microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent resistance to medicines, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological sampling is even less frequent in the case of travelling patients or in basic care - Karolina Böröcz said.
Saves with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is spread from one patient to another through healthcare personnel.
Therefore, hand washing, rubber gloves and masks play a very important role, but also in this regard there are considerable shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA is spread through droplet transmission and direct contact between people, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital rooms are often crowded, beds are often very close together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated by at least a distance of 1.5 metres.
Unfortunately you can also experience - added Karolina Böröcz - that in hospitals of less favorable economic situation is saved with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a greater probability for the infection.
In Karolina Böröcz's view, where appropriate preventive measures are implemented, fewer infections of this type are recorded or the contagion of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government Programme Against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA contagion is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, so it is fought against in all countries.
In England, for example, there is a government programme to prevent and reduce MRSA cases.
The programme appears to be successful, according to the data provided, MRSA infections show a declining trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has as its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and hospital infections due to these pathogens.
Negative alcohol control of the police commander who caused a fatal accident
The official expert report has been made on the case of the fatal accident caused by the police commander of the XXII district.
The possibility that he was driving drunk or in a dazed state can be excluded since then the resigned police commander of the XXII district, who on Tuesday ran over and caused the death of a passerby - reported Friday Attila Morvai, spokesman of the Attorney General's Office of the Capital, after having prepared the expert report on the case.
The expert report confirmed the result of primary alcohol control which had already found that the former police commander did not consume alcoholic beverages before putting himself behind the wheel.
The then chief of the XXII district police station, on Tuesday with his private vehicle turning to Kossuth Lajos Street in the XXII district, ran over a 55-year-old man, who intended to cross the street, but not in the pedestrian-designated area.
(The latter fact, that is, that the pedestrian did not use the zebra to cross the street, according to the regulations of the Transit Code are not mitigating circumstances, the driver must always give way when bending.)
The passerby lost his life after being hospitalized.
As a result, the district police leader resigned and requested his retirement, according to the police statement, because he was very moved by the case.
The investigation of the case is carried out by the Budapest Public Prosecutor ' s Office.
Attila Morvai also said that the former police commander from the beginning collaborated with the prosecutors in charge of the investigation.
EUR 400 million more for infrastructure
Hungarian finance minister János Veres and vice president of the European Investment Bank (EIB) Marta Gajecka signed three credit-limit agreements in Budapest on Friday for a total value of €400 million to finance infrastructure for education, transport and the environment, as well as the energy sector.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved in 2006 a budget of EUR 300 million to finance transport and environmental protection projects in the Hungarian budget, which will be made out of the Cohesion Fund grant, of which the parties had previously signed a credit agreement worth EUR 100 million, the contract they have just signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The EUR 150 million credit agreement is also intended to finance the budget for educational projects.
The EIB approved a total of EUR 300 million for this target for Hungary, on the use of the remaining EUR 150 million the decision will be taken later, with the extension of the credit agreement.
The parties signed a contract for 50 million euros for innovations, which the budget will mainly use for the innovation and research project of Debrecen University.
During the talks they also covered the issue of the construction of the 4th line of the Metro.
It was agreed that by the time Hungary finalizes the details of Metro funding with the EU, it will revert to the issue of whether or not the original contract needs to be modified and how to do so.
According to János Veres, this may take place earlier in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990 the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary worth EUR 8.4 billion.
The interest on the loans is in accordance with EURIBOR and the EIB offers a grace period of 8 years, without charge for keeping the credit available to the debtor.
Bulgaria, the EU Real Estate Paradise
It is admirable the development of the Bulgarian real estate market - the attention of all of Europe is directed towards that Balkan country mentioned above.
What thing, where and those who buy in the EU's even cheaper market, which will quickly get more expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
The preferred objective for real estate acquisitions in Eastern Europe is without a doubt Bulgaria, with its cheap ski slopes apartments and beach chalets.
The mountainous regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are the most preferred, while on the beaches of Albena, the "Costa Dorada", the "Costa del Sol", the ancient Sozopol and Nesebar, but more and more people are also looking for properties in the vicinity of Kavarna and Balchik.
