Fodor and the six by hundreds Hungarians
As reported by the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor, meetings at the expert level will end on Tuesday and Wednesday after the official inauguration, negotiations at the ministerial level on the post-2012 international climate regime will continue.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world discuss the Bali Road Map that provides for post-emission reduction efforts, as set out in the Kyoto Protocol, up to 2012.
There are now lively discussions on the subject between developing and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that it does not wish to negotiate on precise figures at the moment, although it tends to agree that, compared to the 1990 situation, the emission of greenhouse gases will decline by 25 to 40 per cent by 2020.
Another major theme of the conference is whether or not industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are willing to offer material and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement was also reached on the aid to be offered to developing countries.
The support fund, provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be led by a board of directors composed of 16 members, probably within the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF) - writes the "Piac és Profit".
The six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Minister for Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate protection and promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
The minister stated that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent by 2020, regardless of whether or not the "post-2012 agreement" will be signed and is willing to commit itself to reducing even 30 per cent if the other major developed regions of the world and developing countries are also willing to make commitments in accordance with their responsibility and capacities.
Gábor Fodor noted that the signatory countries to the 1997 Kyoto Protocol committed themselves to decline by 5.2 percent, within this the then 15 EU Member States committed themselves to meet an 8 percent decrease.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce the emission of greenhouse gases by 6% compared with the period between 1985 and 87, which our country will comply with - says the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
Much is at stake in Bali, since in two years' time the international agreement on long-term climate policy will have to be signed, because if not, it is certain that its entry into force would be postponed to after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments made in the Kyoto Protocol would not be followed immediately by a new international emission reduction system, the need for which was warned in its most recent report by the IPCC, the UN's international scientific partnership dealing with climate change, which won the Nobel Peace Prize.
This would delay the reduction of emissions and would not prevent an increase of more than 2°C in the average temperature of the Earth, a fact that scientists believe would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
British Army recruits on YouTube
British army units in a video distributor publish recordings of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First the British Air Force (RAD) took advantage of YouTube services: Special units displaced in Afghanistan since March 2006 are uploading videos about their actions against the Taliban - reported the BBC.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are controlled in Kandahar's general body of operations, then sent to London to be loaded to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
There are already 139 recordings coming from the air force soldiers who have been loaded in this way to the Internet and their "channel" has already been seen by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered in the spring of 2007 under the name "defense headsquarters" and publishes videos of both actions perpetrated in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Ministry of the Commonwealth of British Nations (Commonwealth Office) and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally the air force had loaded the videos with recruitment targets, but in the opinion of the Ministry of Defence they also serve to present to the public the true objective of the British army's presence abroad.
This type of propaganda costs practically nothing compared to conventional television spots of recruitment - the defense expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC - but inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the raison d'être of the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans prepared a video game
The army is also concerned about the fact that, in addition to the suspiciously edited and censored recordings, amateur videos also appear in the distributor, for example about the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, the officers speak at most of losses, without however presenting the bloody part of the fights.
In addition, numerous videos recorded in real operations have already been uploaded to the Internet from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan, but the British army has only recently taken advantage of this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different form for recruitment with shooting video games, free downloadable, called America's Army, in which in the middle of a more or less real situation the player can put himself directly in place of the soldiers.
