Banks want to solve the crisis
The American Federal Reserve Bank, the European Central Bank and the British, Swiss and Canadian Central Banks decided to fight the financial market crisis together.
More than one hundred billion dollars will be received in the Monetary Marking by means of tenders.
In these tenders banks auction interest rates for which they are able to lend money.
For example, the American Fed will bid $40 billion, and then another twenty-four billion will be provided by the central banks of Europe and Switzerland.
After the September 11 attacks, it is the first time that central banks of different states have agreed on this coordinated process to protect and lessen the consequences of the financial crisis.
"This step must solve the biggest economic problem, that is, the continued growth of the shortage of free capital that banks could lend," wrote Bernard Baumohl of the Economic Outlook Group in his report for customers.
"This coordinated action by central banks probably reduced the recession in the United States from 65 percent to fifty percent," Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already spent $60 billion on unpaid loans, especially in the United States.
Economists still expect billions in losses.
"Central banks must be really afraid of what awaits them when they decided to take this step," said ABN Amro's leading economist, Kieran Davies.
"It seems that the situation is really wrong," he added.
Central banks fear that they will have the same problems with access to loans and will therefore have to lend more expensive to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and send the American economy into recession with different impacts on the growth of the world economy.
The central banks thus decided, after they did not manage to reduce the so-called LIBOR tariff, London interbank rate that is used for the loan of money in the interbank market.
This means that banks were constantly afraid to lend money even when the Central Banks of the United States, Canada and Britain reduced their interest rates several times during the fall.
"It will have the same effect as another fall in interest rates," he told Reuters agency, Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting.
