A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which describe the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are freely accessible.
The 47 million archival documents, stored on 27 km of shelves to Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were not so far accessible only for a "humanitarian" purpose, i.e. individually and nominated, at the request of a former victim or his successors.
The eleven States responsible for their management - such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to search engines and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
Historians ' access to Bad Arolsen will make it possible to conduct searches "particularly on the displacement of prisoners, the population of camps and the health status of forced workers ", explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Commission of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, a number of States, such as Germany, opposed the opening to the public of these nominative documents, because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
As well as the alleged homosexuality or mental handicap of certain victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been collected after war for a practical purpose: to find the countrymen deported or subjected to compulsory labour and, possibly, to provide them with proof of their internment, in order to open the way for their compensation.
Still today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees deal with tens of thousands of individual petitions.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
" There is nothing fundamentally new to be expected from these documents " , said Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Anti-Semitism Research Centre at the Technische Universität in Berlin in 2006.
