Congress approves the transposition of the Mifid, which came into force 1 November
In parallel with its parliamentary process, which ended today with the vote by Congress on the amendments incorporated into the bill in the Senate, the Government has submitted to a public hearing the regulations that will develop the new law, with the aim of both entering into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of the different groups agreed to highlight the effort made by deputies and senators to negotiate and agree on the best regulations in order to ensure the protection of investors and to regulate in detail the activities of the entities so that the markets function efficiently.
The Mifid, which amends the Securities Market Act, involves modernising financial markets, while strengthening investor protection, improving the supervisory powers of the National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the various supervisors of the European Union.
The new regulation will provide financial advisory services to both specialised firms and natural or legal persons and create a new type of financial services firms (ESIS), financial advisory companies (AFIs), which join securities companies, securities agencies and holding companies.
In addition, it expands the number of systems for the execution of transactions on financial instruments, so that regulated secondary markets are added to multilateral trading systems and order internalization systems, which will compete with existing stockbrokers.
The Act also obliges investment firms to disclose on the market information on key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and risk management and requires them to keep a record of all transactions they carry out, to facilitate supervision by the CNMV.
In its passage through the Congressional Committee on Economics, several modifications were incorporated, among which it emphasizes that securitized debts are considered as a "complex" financial instrument given its high danger to the investor, which has been demonstrated by what happened with the debt of US high-risk mortgages (subprime).
In addition, the transposition of the directive was used to delimit legally the functions that graduates in economics and business can perform 30 years after the adoption in 1977 of the royal decree delimiting the professional functions reserved for economists.
