Venus: twin brother of the Earth.
Despite its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the planet most similar to Earth, something that had not been raised so far. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and swirls at the poles, the same ones that appear also in winter on Earth.
For three decades now, researchers had suspected that rays could exist on Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus the rays are silent from a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, Cris Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles tells the scientific journal "Nature".
According to the famous model of the origin of Urey-Miller's life, the rays caused life on Earth: the storms may have provoked reactions in the ocean that, for their part, would have given rise to the amino acids that are the basic components of life.
On Venus it's not like that: if there was ever life there, that would have to be in one of the first states of evolution," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, on the surface of Venus there can be no life: atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times higher than on Earth and on the surface temperatures of 500°C reign, oscillating in such a way that temperatures can be reached below zero.
"Possibly Venus is an Earth's "diabolic" twin, but he's still a twin," Russell said.
The main objective of the mission "Venus Express" is to answer the question of why Venus, so similar to Earth because of its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since the 1990s there were no special missions, only for research on this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for research on Venus.
The latest results of the research that will be presented in many articles of "Nature", according to the opinion of the researchers, underline not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
"This also shows that neighboring planets have more characteristics common to the Earth than we had supposed," reports ESA.
Despite the already known stormy winds at the North Pole, researchers discovered in the southern polar region also a cloud-shaped vortex that rotates faster.
This phenomenon is reminiscent of wind flows in the high terrestrial atmospheric layers of the poles, as described by a team of researchers from Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet of the Solar System has the mass almost equal to the Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers is almost so large.
This planet also called dawn star or evening star orbit around the Sun nearly 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: a day on Venus is 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and with its atmospheric pressure of 92 bars does not resemble the Earth much, scientists start from the basis that both planets had formed in the same conditions.
On the two planets water had agglomerated that on Earth remained in the oceans, but on Venus it was dissociated in the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had become carbon stones, on Venus it forms most of the atmosphere.
